"Overall, this is a fantastic beer and one that I wish was more readily available. As a Flanders Oud Bruin, it's not the best I've ever had, but I've seen it listed as a fruit lambic (kriek), a Flanders red an Oud Bruin and even an American Wild. There seems to be so much grey area between those styles. Either way, it's a beer that I will make a point to drink anytime I come across it. Just outstanding stuff from Perennial."
""
"Pour is brown with red edges and a tight light brown head. Nose is strange, bready and dough malts abound, a bit musky. Some sour cherry behind but light. Taste is more tart cherry than the nose, the musky bread is there, very strange. Light leathery brett mid palate. Rather full bodied with a strong carbonation."
